name.text: Solving a Quadratic Equation using the Quadratic Formula

questiontext.text:
Solve the following quadratic equation by using the quadratic formula, giving your answer in exact form.

\( {@a*v^2+b*v+c@} = 0 \)

Give your answer as a set containing all of the solutions for \({@v@}\), for example, \( \{ {@v@}_1 ,{@v@}_2 \} \).

Note: To enter a set, write the elements inside “curly braces”, like {1, 2, 3, …}.
The “empty set” should be written as {}.
To enter a square root, \(\sqrt{x}\), you should write sqrt(x).

\({@v@} \in \) [[input:ans]] [[validation:ans]]

[[feedback:prt1]]

generalfeedback.text:
Worked Solution

A good method for solving any quadratic equation is using the quadratic formula.

For the general quadratic equation \(a{@v@}^2+b{@v@}+c = 0 \), the solutions for \({@v@}\) are given by,

\(\displaystyle {@v@} = \frac{ -b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac} }{2a}\)


In this example: \(a = {@a@}\), \(b = {@b@}\) and \(c = {@c@}\), so substituting these values into the quadratic formula gives,

\(\displaystyle {@v@} = \frac{{@(-b)@} \pm \sqrt{{@b^2@}-({@4*a*c@})}}{@2*a@} = {@-b/(2*a)@} \pm {@(sqrt(b^2-4*a*c))/(2*a)@}\)


Therefore \( {@v@} = {@ta1@}\) or \( {@v@} = {@ta2@}\) and so the solution set is,

\({@v@} \in {@{ta1, ta2}@}\)
